# Engineering Principles

← [AGENTS.md](../AGENTS.md) ← [docs/README.md](./README.md)

**Phase:** always
**Owner:** cross-cutting

Universal software engineering principles applied to architecture and code.

---

## SOLID

- **S**ingle Responsibility — one module, one reason to change
- **O**pen/Closed — open for extension, closed for modification
- **L**iskov Substitution — subtypes must be substitutable for base types
- **I**nterface Segregation — no client forced to depend on unused interfaces
- **D**ependency Inversion — depend on abstractions, not concretions

---

## DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)

- Every rule, formula, and constant has exactly one owner
- Cross-reference instead of copying
- Two occurrences of the same logic → extract to shared module

---

## KISS (Keep It Simple)

- Default: simplest correct implementation
- Measure before optimizing
- Never optimize at accuracy's expense

---

## YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It)

- Do not build features "for the future"
- Do not add speculative abstractions
- Do not pre-optimize without profiling evidence

---

## Code-Level Principles

### Fail Fast with Typed Errors

- Pure functions return typed results, not thrown exceptions
- Validate at boundaries — parse, do not trust

### Immutability by Default

- Data structures are read-only unless mutation is explicitly required
- Versioned artifacts — new versions supersede, never in-place edits

### Parse, Do Not Validate

- Every system boundary parses raw data into trusted types
- Internal code works only with trusted, validated types

### Functional Core, Thin Shell

- Business logic is pure functions
- I/O (network, filesystem, external APIs) lives in a thin shell layer
